1
00:00:02,386 --> 00:00:03,387
- Hey, Jake,

2
00:00:03,420 --> 00:00:04,721
guess who just called me?

3
00:00:04,755 --> 00:00:05,822
- The Jerky Boys.
They're back!

4
00:00:05,856 --> 00:00:06,890
- No.
What?

5
00:00:06,923 --> 00:00:08,792
No.
- No.

6
00:00:08,825 --> 00:00:11,328
- D.C. Parlov.
He's in town for LegendCon,

7
00:00:11,362 --> 00:00:12,796
and he has a case for us!

8
00:00:12,829 --> 00:00:13,897
- Oh, my God, oh, my God,
oh, my God!

9
00:00:13,930 --> 00:00:15,332
- Parlov?
Didn't he write

10
00:00:15,366 --> 00:00:16,800
those "Skyfire" books?

11
00:00:16,833 --> 00:00:18,635
I thought he turned out
to be a jerk.

12
00:00:18,669 --> 00:00:19,836
- Yeah, but ever since
Jake and I saved his life,

13
00:00:19,870 --> 00:00:21,405
he's actually been very nice.

14
00:00:21,438 --> 00:00:22,906
He even sent me
a Christmas gift.

15
00:00:22,939 --> 00:00:26,743
A full-scale replica
of the sword of Opadoma.

16
00:00:26,777 --> 00:00:28,412
- Unh!
- Why are you so excited?

17
00:00:28,445 --> 00:00:30,381
You don't care
about those stupid books.

18
00:00:30,414 --> 00:00:31,782
- I actually did read
all of them in prison.

19
00:00:31,815 --> 00:00:33,116
They are the greatest books
I've ever read,

20
00:00:33,149 --> 00:00:34,685
and I've read "Cujo."

21
00:00:34,718 --> 00:00:36,620
- Jake and I really bonded
over "Skyfire."

22
00:00:36,653 --> 00:00:38,121
- Yeah.
- Watch this.

23
00:00:38,154 --> 00:00:39,590
Favorite moment
in the series?

24
00:00:39,623 --> 00:00:41,425
both:
The summoning of Balacastro.

25
00:00:41,458 --> 00:00:43,126
- Second favorite?

26
00:00:43,159 --> 00:00:44,628
both: The Scarlet Feast!
- Third favorite?

27
00:00:44,661 --> 00:00:46,430
both:
When you thought Ka'lar

28
00:00:46,463 --> 00:00:47,631
had been swallowed
by the Norolith,

29
00:00:47,664 --> 00:00:49,366
but had just switched armor

30
00:00:49,400 --> 00:00:50,767
with Samling the Betrayer

31
00:00:50,801 --> 00:00:52,436
in the battle of Vorcastle.

32
00:00:52,469 --> 00:00:53,937
[laughter]
- Fourth favorite?

33
00:00:53,970 --> 00:00:55,906
- Three was plenty.
So was zero.

34
00:00:55,939 --> 00:00:57,674
- Okay, I can see
that you're skeptical, Rosa,

35
00:00:57,708 --> 00:00:59,876
but how about this:
come with us on the case!

36
00:00:59,910 --> 00:01:01,945
I know you think it's dumb,
but "Skyfire" is actually

37
00:01:01,978 --> 00:01:03,947
very smart and dark and adult.

38
00:01:03,980 --> 00:01:05,449
It's not for nerds at all.

39
00:01:05,482 --> 00:01:06,850
Ooh!
On our way there,

40
00:01:06,883 --> 00:01:07,884
should we sing
the elvish hunting song?

41
00:01:07,918 --> 00:01:09,586
- [laughs]

42
00:01:09,620 --> 00:01:10,721
both: * Sharpen your swords

43
00:01:10,754 --> 00:01:12,155
♪ And string your bows

44
00:01:12,188 --> 00:01:13,524
♪ The beasts have gone away

45
00:01:13,557 --> 00:01:16,527
[upbeat music]

46
00:01:16,560 --> 00:01:23,467
♪

47
00:01:33,577 --> 00:01:35,779
- Whoa, look at this place!

48
00:01:35,812 --> 00:01:38,415
Ooh, they're selling
moss wine.

49
00:01:38,449 --> 00:01:40,484
I wonder if it's as gross
as the books say it is.

50
00:01:40,517 --> 00:01:42,519
- I can never get into
any of this crap.

51
00:01:42,553 --> 00:01:43,987
I think the reason
is because it's garbage.

52
00:01:44,020 --> 00:01:45,622
- Rosa, I think
if you just gave it a chance,

53
00:01:45,656 --> 00:01:47,724
you would get hooked.
I mean,

54
00:01:47,758 --> 00:01:49,626
what is it that you do in
your free time that's so cool?

55
00:01:49,660 --> 00:01:51,428
- Fix up old cars
and sell them to celebrities.

56
00:01:51,462 --> 00:01:52,763
That's why I'm friends
with Tom Hardy.

57
00:01:52,796 --> 00:01:54,631
- Right, so we agree
that we're all equally cool.

58
00:01:54,665 --> 00:01:56,467
- Here we go.
This is Parlov's panel.

59
00:01:56,500 --> 00:01:57,868
"Diversity in Fantasy Writing."

60
00:01:57,901 --> 00:01:59,770
- Ooh, the line starts here.

61
00:01:59,803 --> 00:02:01,204
[applause]

62
00:02:01,237 --> 00:02:02,939
- Real diverse
diversity panel.

63
00:02:02,973 --> 00:02:04,775
- And, like,
people always ask me,

64
00:02:04,808 --> 00:02:05,942
"Where do you get your ideas?"

65
00:02:05,976 --> 00:02:08,011
And honestly, Wikipedia.

66
00:02:08,044 --> 00:02:09,946
- I always try
to pull from life.

67
00:02:09,980 --> 00:02:11,615
Queen Tiffany, of course,
was named after

68
00:02:11,648 --> 00:02:12,883
a lovely hostess that I met

69
00:02:12,916 --> 00:02:14,818
in Bonita Springs
in Florida.

70
00:02:14,851 --> 00:02:16,820
- You know, I've always wanted
to write a book myself,

71
00:02:16,853 --> 00:02:19,022
but all I know about is cops,
and there are literally

72
00:02:19,055 --> 00:02:20,824
no more cop stories to tell.
Zero.

73
00:02:20,857 --> 00:02:21,825
- I've actually been
writing a novel.

74
00:02:21,858 --> 00:02:23,627
- Wait, what?

75
00:02:23,660 --> 00:02:24,861
You're writing a book?
When? For who?

76
00:02:24,895 --> 00:02:26,530
- For me—for fun.

77
00:02:26,563 --> 00:02:27,998
Look, I'm not trying
to be an author.

78
00:02:28,031 --> 00:02:29,600
I don't even know
how to go about doing that.

79
00:02:29,633 --> 00:02:31,602
- Parlov! You should show it
to Parlov.

80
00:02:31,635 --> 00:02:32,636
He could probably
get it published.

81
00:02:32,669 --> 00:02:34,805
- No, that's crazy.

82
00:02:34,838 --> 00:02:37,541
Like, I'm sure it's bad.
I don't want to be embarrassed.

83
00:02:37,574 --> 00:02:39,009
- Terry,
you are a great husband,

84
00:02:39,042 --> 00:02:40,877
father, detective,
painter, dancer,

85
00:02:40,911 --> 00:02:42,746
and you're so jacked
you have muscles on your back.

86
00:02:42,779 --> 00:02:44,815
- Everyone has back muscles,
Jake.

87
00:02:44,848 --> 00:02:46,550
- Nuh-huh, my back looks like
the inside of a spoon.

88
00:02:46,583 --> 00:02:47,851
The point is,
you're great at everything.

89
00:02:47,884 --> 00:02:49,653
You're probably great
at writing, too.

90
00:02:49,686 --> 00:02:50,854
- I am not showing Parlov
my book, okay?

91
00:02:50,887 --> 00:02:53,256
- All right.

92
00:02:53,289 --> 00:02:56,527
- Here he comes.
Now just drop it.

93
00:02:56,560 --> 00:02:58,695
- Sorry, I hope that wasn't
too tedious for you.

94
00:02:58,729 --> 00:03:00,531
- It was fascinating,
especially to Terry.

95
00:03:00,564 --> 00:03:01,698
He's a writer,
and he wrote a book.

96
00:03:01,732 --> 00:03:02,966
Would you read it?
both: Dude!

97
00:03:02,999 --> 00:03:04,835
- Sure.
Love to, absolutely.

98
00:03:04,868 --> 00:03:06,269
But listen, there's something
I want you to see.

99
00:03:06,302 --> 00:03:07,838
Come with me, guys, all right?

100
00:03:07,871 --> 00:03:09,606
- Jake!
- What?

101
00:03:09,640 --> 00:03:11,241
Terry, you need to believe
in yourself,

102
00:03:11,274 --> 00:03:13,577
like when Morzak answered
the sorceress' riddle!

103
00:03:13,610 --> 00:03:14,811
- She turned him into a tree,
Jake.

104
00:03:14,845 --> 00:03:16,079
- Yeah, a tree that became

105
00:03:16,112 --> 00:03:17,714
the handle of Prominius' axe.

106
00:03:17,748 --> 00:03:19,583
- Parlov is so far away
already.

107
00:03:19,616 --> 00:03:20,851
- Yeah, good call.
Let's go after him.

108
00:03:20,884 --> 00:03:22,619
- [knocks at door]
Hey.

109
00:03:22,653 --> 00:03:23,654
The desk sergeant said
we're hosting

110
00:03:23,687 --> 00:03:24,855
a forensic sciences course.

111
00:03:24,888 --> 00:03:27,724
- Yes,
taught by Dr. Ronald Yee.

112
00:03:27,758 --> 00:03:30,093
- He revolutionized the field
of forensic entomology.

113
00:03:30,126 --> 00:03:31,995
He is a rock star.

114
00:03:32,028 --> 00:03:33,930
- Oh, please.
Rock stars wish they were he.

115
00:03:33,964 --> 00:03:35,699
The man can tell how long
a corpse had been decomposing

116
00:03:35,732 --> 00:03:37,701
just by studying
the maggots inside.

117
00:03:37,734 --> 00:03:39,002
I'd like to see
Barbra Streisand do that.

118
00:03:39,035 --> 00:03:40,036
- I'm not sure
Barbra Streisand

119
00:03:40,070 --> 00:03:41,938
counts as a rock star, sir.

120
00:03:41,972 --> 00:03:43,707
- She sings in English.
That's rock music.

121
00:03:43,740 --> 00:03:46,076
- Well, it sounds interesting.
Can I sign up?

122
00:03:46,109 --> 00:03:48,745
- [sighs]
Yes, you can,

123
00:03:48,779 --> 00:03:51,281
but here's the thing:
if we do well at this course,

124
00:03:51,314 --> 00:03:52,883
we receive board certification,

125
00:03:52,916 --> 00:03:55,018
which makes us eligible
to receive a grant

126
00:03:55,051 --> 00:03:56,987
to open a field lab
in the precinct,

127
00:03:57,020 --> 00:03:59,022
but...

128
00:03:59,055 --> 00:04:02,659
- Eh—but whenever we have
a speaker come in,

129
00:04:02,693 --> 00:04:04,695
you kind of tend to always

130
00:04:04,728 --> 00:04:06,897
derail these things
with personal stories.

131
00:04:06,930 --> 00:04:08,298
- That's how I learn.
I relate course material

132
00:04:08,331 --> 00:04:09,766
to my experiences.

133
00:04:09,800 --> 00:04:11,134
- Subjective learning.

134
00:04:11,167 --> 00:04:12,869
Millennials.

135
00:04:12,903 --> 00:04:14,037
- I know it's important,
so I promise,

136
00:04:14,070 --> 00:04:15,639
I won't tell any stories,

137
00:04:15,672 --> 00:04:17,340
though sometimes
they do come in handy.

138
00:04:17,373 --> 00:04:18,942
One time,
all the Boyles were in

139
00:04:18,975 --> 00:04:20,811
this fungus cavern, and this
massive mushroom comes—

140
00:04:20,844 --> 00:04:22,145
- Charles.
- I am so sorry.

141
00:04:22,178 --> 00:04:23,313
I slipped right into it.

142
00:04:23,346 --> 00:04:24,848
I'll be good.

143
00:04:24,881 --> 00:04:26,717
- This is my room,
right over here.

144
00:04:26,750 --> 00:04:28,151
Listen, I need just a moment
to clean up.

145
00:04:28,184 --> 00:04:30,086
I had a female visitor
in earlier today

146
00:04:30,120 --> 00:04:31,722
dressed as Concubina.

147
00:04:31,755 --> 00:04:33,089
She got smears of
green body paint

148
00:04:33,123 --> 00:04:34,791
all over everything.

149
00:04:34,825 --> 00:04:36,893
Everything.

150
00:04:38,962 --> 00:04:40,631
- He was talking
about his penis.

151
00:04:40,664 --> 00:04:41,832
- I know, Jake.
- He pulls, Rosa.

152
00:04:41,865 --> 00:04:43,767
He pulls.
That's all I'm saying.

153
00:04:43,800 --> 00:04:44,701
- I can't believe you told him
about my book.

154
00:04:44,735 --> 00:04:46,737
- I'm sorry, Terry, but now

155
00:04:46,770 --> 00:04:47,804
D.C. Parlov is going to
read what you wrote!

156
00:04:47,838 --> 00:04:49,172
How cool is that?

157
00:04:49,205 --> 00:04:50,807
- He's pretty cool.
- Right?

158
00:04:50,841 --> 00:04:52,743
You haven't even told me
what it's about yet.

159
00:04:52,776 --> 00:04:54,077
- Well, it's the story
of a Gorgon warrior...

160
00:04:54,110 --> 00:04:55,879
- Awesome.
- Who betrays his bloodline...

161
00:04:55,912 --> 00:04:57,681
- How could he?
- To marry a Cloud Princess...

162
00:04:57,714 --> 00:04:58,882
- He did it for love.
- Even though

163
00:04:58,915 --> 00:05:00,817
their families are at war.
- No!

164
00:05:00,851 --> 00:05:02,085
All right, no more spoilers.
Send it over to me,

165
00:05:02,118 --> 00:05:03,887
and I'm gonna stay up
all night reading it.

166
00:05:03,920 --> 00:05:05,355
- It's only 150 pages.
- I'm gonna stay up

167
00:05:05,388 --> 00:05:06,823
all the next three nights
reading it.

168
00:05:06,857 --> 00:05:08,659
- Dr. Yee will be here
any minute,

169
00:05:08,692 --> 00:05:09,826
and we need to make
a good impression.

170
00:05:09,860 --> 00:05:11,828
If you need to cough...

171
00:05:11,862 --> 00:05:13,096
cough now.

172
00:05:13,129 --> 00:05:14,898
- [coughing obnoxiously]

173
00:05:14,931 --> 00:05:16,900
- My God, what if I hadn't
said anything?

174
00:05:16,933 --> 00:05:18,168
- Don't worry, I got this.

175
00:05:18,201 --> 00:05:19,836
Nobody sucks up like a Boyle.

176
00:05:19,870 --> 00:05:21,672
Our scoliosis allows us

177
00:05:21,705 --> 00:05:23,674
to bow more deeply
than normal people.

178
00:05:23,707 --> 00:05:25,842
- Huh, here's an idea:
Santiago and I will impress him

179
00:05:25,876 --> 00:05:27,077
with the depth of our
forensic knowledge,

180
00:05:27,110 --> 00:05:29,680
and you can wow him

181
00:05:29,713 --> 00:05:31,982
with your stoic,
silent demeanor.

182
00:05:32,015 --> 00:05:33,717
No stories.
Understood?

183
00:05:33,750 --> 00:05:35,085
- Stoic.
Ah.

184
00:05:35,118 --> 00:05:36,987
- Good morning, everyone.

185
00:05:37,020 --> 00:05:38,655
Thank you for having me
at the Nine-Nine.

186
00:05:38,689 --> 00:05:40,123
Sorry I'm late.
Just had to deal

187
00:05:40,156 --> 00:05:41,725
with some family issues.

188
00:05:41,758 --> 00:05:43,927
Cousins, right?

189
00:05:43,960 --> 00:05:45,796
Okay, before we get technical,

190
00:05:45,829 --> 00:05:46,997
let's talk a bit
about the history of blood.

191
00:05:47,030 --> 00:05:49,065
Does anyone here
know any hemophiliacs?

192
00:05:49,099 --> 00:05:50,433
- [whispering]
So many...

193
00:05:50,466 --> 00:05:51,968
- Now, they played a vital role

194
00:05:52,002 --> 00:05:53,036
in the development
of modern forensics.

195
00:05:53,069 --> 00:05:55,105
Them and leeches.

196
00:05:55,138 --> 00:05:56,740
- My cousin Torvald
is a hemophiliac,

197
00:05:56,773 --> 00:05:58,709
and his wife is a leech farmer.

198
00:05:58,742 --> 00:06:00,243
I say "wife,"
but it's a common-law marriage.

199
00:06:00,276 --> 00:06:01,912
For the longest time,
Boyle wedding ceremonies

200
00:06:01,945 --> 00:06:03,246
were not recognized
in the state.

201
00:06:03,279 --> 00:06:05,148
- Well, here's the situation:

202
00:06:05,181 --> 00:06:06,883
somebody stole my laptop,

203
00:06:06,917 --> 00:06:08,785
which contained
the unpublished manuscript

204
00:06:08,819 --> 00:06:10,921
of book 13 of
"The Skyfire Cycle."

205
00:06:10,954 --> 00:06:13,757
The person left this note.

206
00:06:13,790 --> 00:06:15,425
- "We have your book.

207
00:06:15,458 --> 00:06:17,460
"Pay us $500,000
in the next 24 hours

208
00:06:17,493 --> 00:06:19,162
"or we leak it online.

209
00:06:19,195 --> 00:06:21,031
The first five chapters
are now up."

210
00:06:21,064 --> 00:06:22,933
- They've been downloaded
85,000 times.

211
00:06:22,966 --> 00:06:25,035
- Well, we should probably
go online

212
00:06:25,068 --> 00:06:27,170
and read those chapters in case
there's some clues in there,

213
00:06:27,203 --> 00:06:29,439
and also maybe we'll find out
Qwandor's true parentage?

214
00:06:29,472 --> 00:06:30,807
- Oh that's already
been revealed.

215
00:06:30,841 --> 00:06:32,275
- No, it hasn't.
[gasps]

216
00:06:32,308 --> 00:06:33,476
both:
Unless the prophecy of Dorgon

217
00:06:33,509 --> 00:06:35,045
is indeed true!

218
00:06:35,078 --> 00:06:36,713
But that would mean—

219
00:06:36,747 --> 00:06:37,781
- You seem pretty calm
for somebody

220
00:06:37,814 --> 00:06:38,915
whose book was just stolen.

221
00:06:38,949 --> 00:06:40,050
- Because I know
who took it.

222
00:06:40,083 --> 00:06:41,752
Landon Lawson.

223
00:06:41,785 --> 00:06:43,053
- He was on that panel.
He writes

224
00:06:43,086 --> 00:06:45,088
"The Shadowbringer Saga."
It's garbage.

225
00:06:45,121 --> 00:06:46,923
- So why would Lawson
want to steal your manuscript?

226
00:06:46,957 --> 00:06:48,124
- We both have books
coming out this fall,

227
00:06:48,158 --> 00:06:49,793
and we have a rather public bet

228
00:06:49,826 --> 00:06:51,194
about whose is going
to sell better.

229
00:06:51,227 --> 00:06:52,929
I believe he's leaking
my manuscript online

230
00:06:52,963 --> 00:06:54,931
just to hurt my sales.

231
00:06:54,965 --> 00:06:56,466
You should arrest him.
- Well, we're not going to

232
00:06:56,499 --> 00:06:57,968
do anything until we've seen
all the evidence.

233
00:06:58,001 --> 00:06:59,135
- If this book fails,

234
00:06:59,169 --> 00:07:00,804
that's the end of "Skyfire."

235
00:07:00,837 --> 00:07:03,206
- Let's go take
this son of a bitch down!

236
00:07:03,239 --> 00:07:05,809
Mr. Lawson?
NYPD.

237
00:07:05,842 --> 00:07:08,078
- Let me guess: you're here
about the stolen manuscript?

238
00:07:08,111 --> 00:07:11,214
- So you admit you did it?
Well, that was easy.

239
00:07:11,247 --> 00:07:13,249
- What? No.
Someone stole my manuscript,

240
00:07:13,283 --> 00:07:14,918
and I know who it was:

241
00:07:14,951 --> 00:07:16,953
D.C. Parlov.

242
00:07:16,987 --> 00:07:18,855
both: By Zorton's Sword!

243
00:07:21,224 --> 00:07:23,326
- It's the exact same note
Parlov got.

244
00:07:23,359 --> 00:07:25,128
- I don't see why anybody
would want to steal your book.

245
00:07:25,161 --> 00:07:27,030
"The Skyfire Cycle" makes
"The Shadowbringer Saga"

246
00:07:27,063 --> 00:07:28,431
look like
"The BeastWorm Chronicles."

247
00:07:28,464 --> 00:07:30,200
- You see, Rosa,
"The BeastWorm Chronicles"

248
00:07:30,233 --> 00:07:31,401
are one of the more
simplistic—

249
00:07:31,434 --> 00:07:33,136
- Don't care.
- Yeah.

