00:15:04,254 --> 00:15:05,688
- Uh, then how will you know
which Ka'lar I'm talking about?

503
00:15:05,721 --> 00:15:06,689
It's a very common name
in "Skyfire."

504
00:15:06,722 --> 00:15:08,524
It's like their John.

505
00:15:08,558 --> 00:15:09,992
- He's going
for the briefcase.

506
00:15:10,025 --> 00:15:11,961
- Okay, let's go.

507
00:15:11,994 --> 00:15:13,563
- Don't make your move
until you're close to him.

508
00:15:13,596 --> 00:15:15,231
There's too many civilians.

509
00:15:15,265 --> 00:15:17,700
[tense music]

510
00:15:17,733 --> 00:15:19,969
- Wait, why are there
so many Ka'lars?

511
00:15:20,002 --> 00:15:22,238
- Costume contest
just ended.

512
00:15:22,272 --> 00:15:23,773
That's why he waited until now
to pick up the money.

513
00:15:23,806 --> 00:15:25,708
- I lost him.
Which one is it?

514
00:15:25,741 --> 00:15:26,809
- It's the one headed toward
the service elevator.

515
00:15:26,842 --> 00:15:28,444
- Hey!
Freeze!

516
00:15:28,478 --> 00:15:29,011
NYPD.
Let me see your hands.

517
00:15:29,044 --> 00:15:31,514
- What's going on?

518
00:15:31,547 --> 00:15:33,983
- Doesn't have the briefcase.
I got the wrong Ka'lar.

519
00:15:34,016 --> 00:15:35,451
- I have eyes on him.
- Take him down!

520
00:15:35,485 --> 00:15:37,453
- [grunts]

521
00:15:37,487 --> 00:15:40,623
- Wrong Ka'lar...

522
00:15:40,656 --> 00:15:42,858
- Boyle's not
in the interrogation room.

523
00:15:42,892 --> 00:15:44,794
- He couldn't have gotten far.
He can't see.

524
00:15:44,827 --> 00:15:46,596
- You can go a long way
on muscle memory alone.

525
00:15:46,629 --> 00:15:47,997
One time, I sleepwalked

526
00:15:48,030 --> 00:15:49,499
to the M&M's store
in Times Square.

527
00:15:49,532 --> 00:15:49,999
[loud banging]
- Oh, oh!

528
00:15:50,032 --> 00:15:52,768
- Stairwell.

529
00:15:52,802 --> 00:15:53,769
Oh, God, oh, God, oh, God.

530
00:15:53,803 --> 00:15:54,870
- I'm okay.

531
00:15:54,904 --> 00:15:55,871
It's okay.
[screams]

532
00:15:55,905 --> 00:15:57,607
Sorry, stranger.

533
00:15:57,640 --> 00:15:58,874
I just can't see anything
at all,

534
00:15:58,908 --> 00:16:00,776
and it's really scary
being touched.

535
00:16:00,810 --> 00:16:02,645
- Are you okay?
- Yes.

536
00:16:02,678 --> 00:16:03,913
Just return me
to the 99th precinct.

537
00:16:03,946 --> 00:16:05,815
- Boyle, it's us.

538
00:16:05,848 --> 00:16:07,683
Where were you going?
Why would you leave

539
00:16:07,717 --> 00:16:09,285
that windowless supply closet
we locked you in?

540
00:16:09,319 --> 00:16:11,721
Ah, yes, hearing it,
I understand why.

541
00:16:11,754 --> 00:16:13,022
- I was trying to get
to the locker room

542
00:16:13,055 --> 00:16:14,757
to steam the mask off
in the shower

543
00:16:14,790 --> 00:16:16,659
so you guys could
still get certified.

544
00:16:16,692 --> 00:16:17,827
- Wait.

545
00:16:17,860 --> 00:16:19,962
You were trying to help us?

546
00:16:19,995 --> 00:16:21,664
Even though you'll be stuck
in this mask for five days?

547
00:16:21,697 --> 00:16:23,666
- Five days?

548
00:16:23,699 --> 00:16:25,635
Well, I know how important
the course was to you.

549
00:16:25,668 --> 00:16:27,503
- It's not.

550
00:16:27,537 --> 00:16:29,305
Not anymore.
- [screams]

551
00:16:29,339 --> 00:16:30,940
I'm so sorry.

552
00:16:30,973 --> 00:16:33,576
I just cannot see at all.

553
00:16:33,609 --> 00:16:34,777
- I can't believe it!

554
00:16:34,810 --> 00:16:36,912
Now I'm out $1/2 million!

555
00:16:36,946 --> 00:16:38,714
What am I supposed to do now?

556
00:16:38,748 --> 00:16:40,550
Write another
"Compendium of Beasts"?

557
00:16:40,583 --> 00:16:42,051
Do you have any idea
how hard it is

558
00:16:42,084 --> 00:16:45,888
to find enough interns
to slap that crap together?

559
00:16:45,921 --> 00:16:46,922
God!

560
00:16:46,956 --> 00:16:48,758
- Don't worry about him.

561
00:16:48,791 --> 00:16:50,660
At least we got
to stop that thief

562
00:16:50,693 --> 00:16:52,328
from releasing
any more chapters.

563
00:16:52,362 --> 00:16:53,963
All we're out is some money,
plus I've got insurance,

564
00:16:53,996 --> 00:16:55,531
so I'm going to
get it all back.

565
00:16:55,565 --> 00:16:56,532
By the way, Detective Jeffords,

566
00:16:56,566 --> 00:16:58,033
while we were waiting,

567
00:16:58,067 --> 00:16:59,669
I had an opportunity
to read your manuscript.

568
00:16:59,702 --> 00:17:01,537
- Oh, don't worry about that.

569
00:17:01,571 --> 00:17:03,373
It's a work in progress.

570
00:17:03,406 --> 00:17:04,940
Has a lot of changes I—

571
00:17:04,974 --> 00:17:06,709
- No, no, no, it was great.
Truly.

572
00:17:06,742 --> 00:17:08,811
Fantastic. I mean,
it was so fresh, you know?

573
00:17:08,844 --> 00:17:10,713
It had a really unique
point of view.

574
00:17:10,746 --> 00:17:12,047
I sent it on
to my publishers.

575
00:17:12,081 --> 00:17:13,649
Thank you for allowing me
to read it.

576
00:17:13,683 --> 00:17:15,050
And I want to thank you all

577
00:17:15,084 --> 00:17:17,019
for your hard, hard work
on this case.

578
00:17:17,052 --> 00:17:18,621
Appreciate it.

579
00:17:18,654 --> 00:17:19,989
- [breathing excitedly]

580
00:17:20,022 --> 00:17:21,724
Ooh, did you hear that?

581
00:17:21,757 --> 00:17:22,925
He loved it.

582
00:17:22,958 --> 00:17:25,361
D.C. Parlov loved my writing!

583
00:17:25,395 --> 00:17:26,929
You were wrong!

584
00:17:26,962 --> 00:17:29,098
- And being wrong
never felt so right.

585
00:17:29,131 --> 00:17:31,033
Oh, that sounded cool.
Did I just make up a hit song?

586
00:17:31,066 --> 00:17:33,403
♪ Being wrong
never felt so right ♪

587
00:17:33,436 --> 00:17:35,738
♪ With the Addams Family
staying up all night ♪

588
00:17:35,771 --> 00:17:36,939
Yep, I was right.
It's a hit.

589
00:17:36,972 --> 00:17:38,841
- I gotta go call Sharon!

590
00:17:38,874 --> 00:17:40,643
- All righty.
Well, congratulations, Sarge!

591
00:17:40,676 --> 00:17:41,777
And don't forget about us

592
00:17:41,811 --> 00:17:43,646
when you become
a famous author.

593
00:17:43,679 --> 00:17:45,615
Terry's writing sucks.
Parlov is lying to him.

594
00:17:45,648 --> 00:17:46,582
- What?
Why?

595
00:17:46,616 --> 00:17:47,983
- I don't know.

596
00:17:48,017 --> 00:17:49,919
He's buttering him up...

597
00:17:49,952 --> 00:17:51,821
because Lawson and Parlov

598
00:17:51,854 --> 00:17:53,989
stole their own books!

599
00:17:54,023 --> 00:17:55,591
♪ Well, they stole
their own books ♪

600
00:17:55,625 --> 00:17:56,759
♪ It's plain to see

601
00:17:56,792 --> 00:17:57,827
♪ But who's on the case

602
00:17:57,860 --> 00:18:00,596
♪ The Addams Family

603
00:18:00,630 --> 00:18:02,865
♪ Terry is Gomez,
I'm Cousin It ♪

604
00:18:02,898 --> 00:18:03,933
♪ You are Wednesday,
let's do this ♪

605
00:18:08,003 --> 00:18:09,539
- Why do you think these guys
are in it together?

606
00:18:09,572 --> 00:18:11,106
They hate each other.
They spent an hour

607
00:18:11,140 --> 00:18:13,409
arguing over the name
of the dragon in "The Hobbit."

608
00:18:13,443 --> 00:18:14,444
- "Smog."
- "Smowg."

609
00:18:14,477 --> 00:18:15,878
- Smog!
- Smowg!

610
00:18:15,911 --> 00:18:17,613
- [yelling] Smog!
- [yelling] Smowg!

611
00:18:17,647 --> 00:18:19,582
- It's "Smowg," by the way—

612
00:18:19,615 --> 00:18:22,117
point Lawson—but yes,
they're mortal enemies,

613
00:18:22,151 --> 00:18:23,586
which is why they think
we'll never suspect them

614
00:18:23,619 --> 00:18:24,887
of being in cahoots.

615
00:18:24,920 --> 00:18:26,522
Oh, but they cahooted, Rosa.

616
00:18:26,556 --> 00:18:28,991
They cahooted all over us.

617
00:18:29,024 --> 00:18:30,526
- Gross.
Why'd they leak their chapters?

618
00:18:30,560 --> 00:18:32,628
- To get people excited,

619
00:18:32,662 --> 00:18:34,830
like when Carly Rae Jepsen
puts out an amazing single,

620
00:18:34,864 --> 00:18:36,098
and you have to wait six weeks
for the album to come out.

621
00:18:36,131 --> 00:18:37,667
She's great.
I'm not apologizing.

622
00:18:37,700 --> 00:18:39,569
- So Parlov contacted Terry
because he knows

623
00:18:39,602 --> 00:18:41,471
Sarge is a super-fan
and can be manipulated.

624
00:18:41,504 --> 00:18:43,473
- Yes, he's been giving Terry
presents since last year.

625
00:18:43,506 --> 00:18:44,840
- And Terry's novel gave Parlov

626
00:18:44,874 --> 00:18:45,841
another chance
to manipulate him.

627
00:18:45,875 --> 00:18:47,643
Unless...

628
00:18:47,677 --> 00:18:49,912
is it possible Parlov actually
likes Sarge's writing?

629
00:18:49,945 --> 00:18:51,914
- Read the first sentence.

630
00:18:51,947 --> 00:18:53,583
- Yep, Parlov did it.
- Very much so.

631
00:18:53,616 --> 00:18:55,585
Gah!
Now I have to tell Sarge

632
00:18:55,618 --> 00:18:57,887
that his fantasy novel stinks.

633
00:18:57,920 --> 00:19:00,556
This is the hardest part
of being a cop.

634
00:19:00,590 --> 00:19:02,658
- Now, there are issues
with RFLP testing,

635
00:19:02,692 --> 00:19:04,960
as there are
with every technique, but...

636
00:19:04,994 --> 00:19:06,862
Captain, I thought you said

637
00:19:06,896 --> 00:19:08,598
your friend removed his mask
and left.

638
00:19:08,631 --> 00:19:10,700
- I forgot to lube up his face.

639
00:19:10,733 --> 00:19:12,535
- We failed to listen
to the instructions.

640
00:19:12,568 --> 00:19:14,604
- That is incredibly careless.

641
00:19:14,637 --> 00:19:16,205
- I know, and it means
we won't receive

642
00:19:16,238 --> 00:19:17,940
our certification,
and I'm okay with that.

643
00:19:17,973 --> 00:19:19,975
Unless my honesty—
- No, it's off the table.

644
00:19:20,009 --> 00:19:22,011
- And I'm okay with that.

645
00:19:22,044 --> 00:19:24,013
- Well, anyway, RFLP testing

646
00:19:24,046 --> 00:19:26,015
was designed to localize
genetic disorders, and it—

647
00:19:26,048 --> 00:19:29,018
- Ooh, my cousin Donna
has a genetic disorder

648
00:19:29,051 --> 00:19:30,620
where her lips
were made of cartilage,

649
00:19:30,653 --> 00:19:32,722
meaning her mouth
is technically a beak.

650
00:19:32,755 --> 00:19:34,156
- I don't see how that pertains
to anything—

651
00:19:34,189 --> 00:19:36,025
- No, let him talk.
I want to hear it.

652
00:19:36,058 --> 00:19:37,893
Boyle, tell us about
your cousin's beak.

653
00:19:37,927 --> 00:19:40,129
- Well, she runs marathons

654
00:19:40,162 --> 00:19:43,032
to raise money for other people
afflicted with "bird-face."

655
00:19:43,065 --> 00:19:44,233
There are only two of them.

656
00:19:44,266 --> 00:19:45,067
They're her kids.

657
00:19:45,100 --> 00:19:46,569
- Oh, Sarge!

658
00:19:46,602 --> 00:19:47,603
Funny seeing you here.

659
00:19:47,637 --> 00:19:49,939
Oh, that reminds me.

660
00:19:49,972 --> 00:19:51,541
I have to tell you something.
What was it?

661
00:19:51,574 --> 00:19:52,975
- Out with it, Peralta.

662
00:19:53,008 --> 00:19:54,644
- Okay, fine.
Here it goes.

663
00:19:54,677 --> 00:19:56,746
I think that—
- Parlov hated my book.

664
00:19:56,779 --> 00:19:59,181
He only said he liked it
so I wouldn't figure out

665
00:19:59,214 --> 00:20:01,651
he and Lawson
stole their own manuscripts.

666
00:20:01,684 --> 00:20:03,052
- You figured it out.
- Well, I had a gut feeling,

667
00:20:03,085 --> 00:20:05,054
so I went digging.

668
00:20:05,087 --> 00:20:06,656
I got a warrant
for Parlov's browser history.

669
00:20:06,689 --> 00:20:08,724
He searched
"how to liquidate Bitcoins"

670
00:20:08,758 --> 00:20:10,926
three days before
the laptops were stolen.

671
00:20:10,960 --> 00:20:12,628
- Man, I bet that browser
history was a nightmare, huh?

672
00:20:12,662 --> 00:20:14,196
- Oh, you have no idea.
- Yeah.

673
00:20:14,229 --> 00:20:16,198
- Anyway, I questioned them,
and they confessed.

674
00:20:16,231 --> 00:20:17,767
- I can't go to prison, okay?

675
00:20:17,800 --> 00:20:20,069
I know I seem tough,
but I'm not.

676
00:20:20,102 --> 00:20:21,571
I went to Bennington.

677
00:20:21,604 --> 00:20:22,304
- Ew.
- I'm sorry Parlov

678
00:20:22,337 --> 00:20:23,673
didn't like your book.

679
00:20:23,706 --> 00:20:25,274
And I didn't.
And also Rosa.

680
00:20:25,307 --> 00:20:27,176
Why did I add that?
- No, it's okay.

681
00:20:27,209 --> 00:20:28,544
At least I won't waste
any more time

682
00:20:28,578 --> 00:20:29,945
trying to be a writer.

683
00:20:29,979 --> 00:20:31,647
- Wait,
let me ask you a question.

684
00:20:31,681 --> 00:20:33,182
Are you a better cop now
than when you started?

685
00:20:33,215 --> 00:20:35,618
- Nope.
- Wasn't talking to you.

686
00:20:35,651 --> 00:20:37,987
- Yeah.
I look back at my old cases

687
00:20:38,020 --> 00:20:40,022
and I can't believe how long

688
00:20:40,055 --> 00:20:41,156
it took me
to figure things out.

689
00:20:41,190 --> 00:20:42,291
- Yeah, but you worked on it,

690
00:20:42,324 --> 00:20:43,593
and you kept working, and now,

691
00:20:43,626 --> 00:20:45,961
12 to 40 years later—

692
00:20:45,995 --> 00:20:47,597
I don't have a good sense of
your age—

693
00:20:47,630 --> 00:20:49,164
you're a great cop
who got a "gut feeling"

694
00:20:49,198 --> 00:20:51,033
and solved a huge case.

695
00:20:51,066 --> 00:20:52,635
- So you think
I should keep writing?

696
00:20:52,668 --> 00:20:54,570
- I mean, you might not
become a huge famous author,

697
00:20:54,604 --> 00:20:56,038
but you'll get better,

698
00:20:56,071 --> 00:20:57,172
and if it makes you happy,

699
00:20:57,206 --> 00:20:58,974
it can't be that bad.

700
00:20:59,008 --> 00:21:00,142
Sheryl Crow, she's great.
I won't apologize.

701
00:21:00,175 --> 00:21:02,177
- And who knows?
Claire Essalgorn

702
00:21:02,211 --> 00:21:03,579
didn't start writing the first
"Crimson Portal" novel

703
00:21:03,613 --> 00:21:06,015
until she was 60.

704
00:21:06,048 --> 00:21:07,983
I started reading it because
the character looks like me.

705
00:21:08,017 --> 00:21:10,052
I kept reading it
because it's so good!

706
00:21:10,085 --> 00:21:12,187
- Rosa, you did get hooked,
you big nerd!

707
00:21:12,221 --> 00:21:13,656
- This heroine is my heroin.

708
00:21:13,689 --> 00:21:15,290
- Oh, such a dweebus.
I love it!

709
00:21:15,324 --> 00:21:18,027
- Speaking of which,
Parlov's laptop is in evidence.

710
00:21:18,060 --> 00:21:19,061
Want to go read
the new "Skyfire" book?

711
00:21:19,094 --> 00:21:21,063
- Oh, I don't know.

712
00:21:21,096 --> 00:21:23,032
I mean, he's such a bad guy.

713
00:21:23,065 --> 00:21:24,600
Do we even like his books
anymore?

714
00:21:24,634 --> 00:21:26,736
[chuckles]

715
00:21:26,769 --> 00:21:27,737
both:
♪ Sharpen your swords

716
00:21:27,770 --> 00:21:29,204
♪ And string your bows

717
00:21:29,238 --> 00:21:30,806
♪ The beasts have gone away

718
00:21:30,840 --> 00:21:32,775
- Not a doctor.
- Shh.

